Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? Reference Assistant, Evenings, Seasonal Montreal , QC Description Position Number: 50013552 / S0025 Department: Information Services Grade: LA-C Campus: Sir George Williams (Downtown) Salary: $28.79 - $34.65 per hour Union/Association/HR Policy: CULEU Posting deadline: August 22, 2023To
apply for this position please visit: https://www.concordia.ca/hr/jobs/openings/staff-positions.html Recognized as Canada’s top university under the age of 50, and one of Montreal’s top Employers, Concordia University is the place to be if you are looking to grow, contribute and innovate in a dynamic and multicultural environment. Be part of a community that addresses society’s big challenges, supports your personal and professional growth, and makes a real impact in building a more sustainable world. As a member of our community, you will have access to comprehensive benefits, a defined pension plan and numerous on site well-being facilities such as a state of the art gym and health clinic as well as a variety of educational and cultural opportunities. NOTE: This posting represents a part-time, seasonal position for the Fall and Winter semesters working Monday to Thursday from 1 pm to 9 pm for 28 hours per week, with a start date of September 11, 2023. This position is based on the SGW campus. SCOPE Reporting to the Head, Information Services, and under the supervision of the Information Services Supervisor, the incumbent performs tasks of a complex nature associated with collection development, reference (in person and online), and library instruction, with functional guidance from the Librarians; performs other duties which may be assigned. PRIMARY RESPONSIBILITIES • Provide assistance to users according to established procedures. • Provide assistance at the service desks, and in the office; answer directional and information questions made in person, by phone or online (chat, email, etc.); refer all other questions to the appropriate Librarian. • Assist with preparation of orientations and instruction programs, as assigned; assist with preparation of collection awareness displays in public areas, as assigned. • Assist with inputting and maintenance of general and subject specific handouts, as assigned. • Encourage users to abide by the Library’s Code of Conduct; report problems to Concordia Security as needed. • Perform bibliographic checking and searching of online library catalogues, specialized collections, electronic and print catalogues of publishers and vendors when requested by Librarians. • Assist Librarians in carrying out tasks related to special projects (e.g. preparation of bibliographies, comparison of collections, surveys and reports). • Assist with the maintenance of the Reference collection according to established procedures; assist library users on the use of equipment. • Clear, sort and shelve materials in the Reference collection. • Assist in keeping the Reference collection up-to-date, including filing updates for updating loose-leaf and other services. • Assist with the maintenance of equipment; report problems with computer workstations and printers. • Assist with secretarial duties; assist with maintenance of office photocopier and printers; assist with distribution of departmental mail. • Record relevant statistics. • Participate in evaluating established procedures and make suggestions for improvement to the Unit Head and to the Information Services Supervisor. QUALIFICATIONS • Diploma of Collegial Studies (3-year technical DEC) in Information and Library Technologies. • Excellent interpersonal skills are essential; this must include proven aptitude for and interest in service-oriented work; demonstrated ability to handle queries and complaints with courtesy, tact, and good judgement. • Proven ability to interpret policies and to solve problems with flexibility and good judgment. • Ability to organize work, establish priorities, and to perform clerical duties with special attention to accuracy, details, and deadlines; the ability to work with a minimum of supervision is essential. • Ability to work cooperatively with supervisors and other staff members is required. • Demonstrated knowledge of Outlook and Windows and of managing files in a Windows environment is required. • Good knowledge (Level 4) of spoken and written English; basic knowledge (Level 3) of spoken French; fluency is preferred. • Basic knowledge of Microsoft Word and Excel is required; knowledge of PowerPoint is an asset. • Knowledge of Internet navigation skills is required. • Demonstrated ability to locate and interpret bibliographic records and documents on a variety of online platforms as required. • Ability to learn new procedures and technologies and adapt to changing technologies. • Physical stamina required to shelve Reference materials. • Work requires long periods of standing of at least 90 minutes. Moderate physical effort is required to push a book truck, and to handle books and computer equipment. • Have physical ability to lift/carry/move without assistance up to 4.5 kg (10 lbs.) and to push a book truck weighing up to 300lbs. Due to the volume of applications, only selected candidates will be contacted by our Talent Team. Concordia University is an English-language institution of higher learning at which the primary language of instruction and research is English. Since this position supports academic and administrative functions of the university, proficiency in English and French, as indicated, is required. IMPORTANT: The language and computer skills of short-listed candidates will be tested. Territorial Acknowledgement Concordia University is located on unceded Indigenous lands. The Kanien’kehá:ka Nation is recognized as the custodians of the lands and waters on which we gather today. Tiohtià:ke/Montreal is historically known as a gathering place for many First Nations. Today, it is home to a diverse population of Indigenous and other peoples. We respect the continued connections with the past, present and future in our ongoing relationships with Indigenous and other peoples within the Montreal community. Employment Equity Concordia University is strongly committed to employment equity within its community, and to recruiting a diverse faculty and staff. The University encourages applications from all qualified candidates, including women, members of visible minorities, Indigenous persons, members of sexual minorities, persons with disabilities, and others who may contribute to diversification; candidates are invited to self-identify in their applications. As part of your application, you will be asked to complete a diversity survey. This information is voluntary and any information collected for this purpose is confidential and cannot be accessed by search committees or human resources employees. Results will be aggregated and used to help Concordia achieve its goal to see all members of our community not only reflected, but welcomed, included and supported in their efforts to contribute to all areas of university life. Accessibility Concordia desires to increase diversity among its community members and we strive to make our recruitment processes as accessible as possible and provide accommodations as required for applicants. If you are contacted for an interview and anticipate needing accommodations during the process, please contact, in confidence, hr-employment@concordia.ca Immigration Status All qualified candidates are encouraged to apply; however, Canadian and Permanent Residents will be given priority. To comply with the Government of Canada’s reporting requirements, the University is obliged to gather information about applicants’ status as either Permanent Residents of Canada or Canadian citizens. Compensation $28.79 - $34.65 Closes: 22 August, 2023 Concordia University Library Montreal , QC Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
